I'm an AI language model and cannot directly create or host an HTML website for you. However, I can provide you with a simple example of the structure of an HTML file for a database-like website that you can use as a starting point. You can then modify it according to your needs and extend it with additional features.

1. Create a new HTML file (e.g. `index.html`):

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">

<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>My Database Website</title>
    <!-- Add your CSS file here -->
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css">
    <!-- Add JavaScript file here -->
    <script src="scripts.js" defer></script>
</head>

<body>
    <header>
        <h1>My Database Website</h1>
    </header>
    <main>
        <section class="search">
            <h2>Search</h2>
            <input type="text" id="search-input" placeholder="Search...">
            <button id="search-button">Search</button>
        </section>
        <section class="results">
            <h2>Results</h2>
            <table>
                <thead>
                    <tr>
                        <th>ID</th>
                        <th>Name</th>
                        <th>Email</th>
                        <th>Phone</th>
                    </tr>
                </thead>
                <tbody id="results-table">
                    <!-- Rows will be added dynamically -->
                </tbody>
            </table>
        </section>
    </main>
    <footer>
        <p>&copy; 2022 MyDatabaseWebsite. All Rights Reserved.</p>
    </footer>
</body>

</html>
```

2. Create a new CSS file (e.g. `styles.css`), and style the page to your preferred look:

```css
body {
    font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
    max-width: 800px;
    margin: auto;
}

header, footer {
    text-align: center;
    background-color: #333;
    color: white;
    padding: 1rem;
}

.main {
    margin-top: 2rem;
}

table {
    width: 100%;
    border-collapse: collapse;
}

table th, table td {
    border: 1px solid #ccc;
    padding: 10px;
    text-align: left;
}

table th {
    background-color: #efefef;
}
```

3. Create a new JavaScript file (e.g. `scripts.js`) to handle interaction with the data and the page elements:

```javascript
document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
    const searchButton = document.getElementById('search-button');
    const searchInput = document.getElementById('search-input');
    const resultsTable = document.getElementById('results-table');

    const data = [
        // Example data, which can be replaced by actual data from a backend API or a database
        { id: 1, name: 'John Doe', email: 'john.doe@example.com', phone: '555-123456' },
        { id: 2, name: 'Jane Doe', email: 'jane.doe@example.com', phone: '555-987654' }
    ];

    searchButton.addEventListener('click', () => {
        const searchValue = searchInput.value.trim();
        const results = data.filter(item => item.name.toLowerCase().includes(searchValue.toLowerCase()));
        displayResults(results);
    });

    function displayResults(results) {
        resultsTable.innerHTML = '';

        for (const result of results) {
            const row = document.createElement('tr');
            row.innerHTML = `
                <td>${result.id}</td>
                <td>${result.name}</td>
                <td>${result.email}</td>
                <td>${result.phone}</td>
            `;
            resultsTable.appendChild(row);
        }
    }
});
```

Note that the example data provided in the `scripts.js` file is just an example. In a real project, you'd probably use an API or fetch the data from the actual database.

To run this example on your machine, create the three different files as described (`index.html`, `styles.css`, and `scripts.js`) with the provided content, and then open the `index.html` file in your web browser.

To create a website that searches for the nearest bar closest to the user's location, we'll use HTML, CSS, JavaScript, and a Google Maps API. This code snippet will provide a simple example. In an actual production website, you would want to style it professionally and consider using a framework or library for better structure and user experience.

This example assumes you have an API key for Google Maps. You can get one from the [Google Cloud Platform Console](https://cloud.google.com/console/google/maps-apis).

1. Create an 'index.html' file with the following code:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
  <head>
    <title>Find Nearby Bars</title>
    <style>
      /* Add some basic styling */
      body {
        font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
        text-align: center;
      }
      #map {
        height: 400px;
        width: 100%;
      }
    </style>
  </head>
  <body>
    <h1>Find Nearby Bars</h1>
    <button onclick="getNearestBar()">Find nearest bar</button>
    <div id="map"></div>

    <!-- Add your Google Maps API key below and include the Maps JavaScript API and Places Library -->
    <script src="https://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/js?key=YOUR_API_KEY&libraries=places"></script>
    <script src="app.js"></script>
  </body>
</html>
```

2. Create an 'app.js' file with the following JavaScript code:

```javascript
let map;
let service;
let userLocation;

function initMap() {
  // Initialize the map centered in San Francisco by default
  const defaultCenter = { lat: 37.7749, lng: -122.4194 };
  map = new google.maps.Map(document.getElementById("map"), {
    center: defaultCenter,
    zoom: 14,
  });

  service = new google.maps.places.PlacesService(map);
}

function getNearestBar() {
  if (navigator.geolocation) {
    navigator.geolocation.getCurrentPosition(
      (position) => {
        userLocation = {
          lat: position.coords.latitude,
          lng: position.coords.longitude,
        };

        map.setCenter(userLocation);

        const request = {
          location: userLocation,
          radius: 5000,
          type: "bar",
        };

        service.nearbySearch(request, processResults);
      },
      () => {
        alert("Error: Failed to get your location. Please allow access.");
      }
    );
  } else {
    alert("Error: Your browser doesn't support geolocation.");
  }
}

function processResults(results, status) {
  if (status === google.maps.places.PlacesServiceStatus.OK) {
    const nearestBar = results[0];

    new google.maps.Marker({
      position: nearestBar.geometry.location,
      map: map,
    });

    map.setZoom(16);
    map.setCenter(nearestBar.geometry.location);
  } else {
    alert("Error: No bars found nearby.");
  }
}

// Initialize the map
initMap();
```

Now, if you open 'index.html' in your browser and click the "Find nearest bar" button, it should ask for your location, then display the nearest bar on the map.

