Sure! In this example, we will implement a simple login page authentication using JavaScript and a mock backend provided by the `json-server`. Keep in mind that this example is for educational purposes only, and you should use a proper authentication method, like OAuth or JWT tokens, in a real-world application.

Follow these steps:

1. Install json-server globally using npm (Node.js Package Manager):

```sh
npm install -g json-server
```

2. Create a new file `db.json` inside your project folder for our mock backend data:

```json
{
  "users": [
    {
      "id": 1,
      "email": "user@example.com",
      "password": "user123" 
    }
  ]
}
```

3. Start the `json-server` using the following command:

```sh
json-server --watch db.json
```

4. Update your HTML code to include an error message element and load the JavaScript file:

```html
<!-- Add this inside the head tag -->
<script src="script.js" defer></script>

<!-- Add an error message element inside the form, after the button -->
<form class="login-form">
  <!-- ... -->
  <button type="submit">Log In</button>
  <p class="error-message" hidden></p>
</form>
```

5. Create a new file `script.js` to handle login and authentication using JavaScript:

```javascript
document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
  const loginForm = document.querySelector('.login-form');
  const errorMessage = document.querySelector('.error-message');

  loginForm.addEventListener('submit', async (event) => {
    event.preventDefault();

    const email = event.target.email.value;
    const password = event.target.password.value;

    const isAuthenticated = await authenticateUser(email, password);

    if (isAuthenticated) {
      // Redirect to your desired page when the authentication is successful
      window.location.href = '/home.html';
    } else {
      errorMessage.innerText = 'Invalid email or password';
      errorMessage.hidden = false;
    }
  });
});

async function authenticateUser(email, password) {
  try {
    const response = await fetch('http://localhost:3000/users');
    const users = await response.json();

    const matchingUser = users.find(
      (user) => user.email === email && user.password === password
    );

    return !!matchingUser;

  } catch (error) {
    console.error('Error fetching data:', error);
    return false;
  }
}
```

This will create a simple authentication system for your login page, validating email and password input against the mock backend created by `json-server`.

Remember that this solution is only meant for educational purposes, and it is not suitable for real-world applications. In a real app, you shouldn't store the password as plain text and should use secure tokens for authentication.

