Creating a full-stack web application for CRUD (Create, Read, Update, Delete) operations requires a frontend, a backend, and a database. In this example, we will use the following technologies:

- Frontend: HTML, CSS, JavaScript, and Bootstrap
- Backend: Node.js with Express.js
- Database: MongoDB with Mongoose

You will need Node.js, npm (bundled with Node.js), and MongoDB installed on your system to follow this example.

1. Create a new directory and navigate to it in your terminal:

```bash
mkdir crud_app
cd crud_app
```

2. Initialize a Node.js project by running the following command and following the prompts:

```bash
npm init
```

3. Install required Node.js packages:

```bash
npm install express mongoose ejs
```

4. Add a new file `server.js`, and add this code:

```javascript
const express = require('express');
const mongoose = require('mongoose');
const bodyParser = require('body-parser');
const app = express();

// MongoDB setup
mongoose.connect('mongodb://localhost/crud_app', {
  useNewUrlParser: true,
  useUnifiedTopology: true,
  useFindAndModify: false,
})
  .then(() => console.log('Connected to MongoDB'))
  .catch(err => console.error('Error connecting to MongoDB', err));

// Model
const Item = mongoose.model('Item', new mongoose.Schema({
  name: { type: String, required: true },
}));

// Middleware
app.use(bodyParser.urlencoded({ extended: true }));
app.set('view engine', 'ejs');

// Routes
app.get('/', async (req, res) => {
  const items = await Item.find();
  res.render('index', { items });
});

app.post('/items', async (req, res) => {
  const newItem = new Item({ name: req.body.name });
  await newItem.save();
  res.redirect('/');
});

app.put('/items/:id', async (req, res) => {
  const updatedItem = await Item.findByIdAndUpdate(req.params.id, { name: req.body.name });
  res.redirect('/');
});

app.delete('/items/:id', async (req, res) => {
  const deletedItem = await Item.findByIdAndRemove(req.params.id);
  res.redirect('/');
});

// Start server
const port = 3000;
app.listen(port, () => console.log(`Server running at http://localhost:${port}`));
```

5. Create an `index.ejs` file in a new folder called `views` with the following content:

```html
