    };

    // Send the message
    string messageId = await FirebaseMessaging.DefaultInstance.SendAsync(message);
    Console.WriteLine($"Successfully sent message with messageId: {messageId}");
}
```

4. Call the `SendMessageAsync` method with the appropriate registration token and dial code when you want to dial the code on the Android device from your C# Windows application.

Now, when you send a message from your C# application, the Android app will receive the message, extract the dial code, and perform the dialing operation. Note that this method doesn't require the PC and phone to be on the same network but does require the Android app to be connected to the internet to receive FCM messages.

To send an ADB command with C#, you can use the `Process` class in C# to execute the `adb` program and pass the required command as an argument. Here is an example code:

```
using System.Diagnostics;

// Specify the ADB command to be sent
string command = "adb shell am start -n com.example.app/.MainActivity";

// Execute the ADB command
ProcessStartInfo startInfo = new ProcessStartInfo();
startInfo.WindowStyle = ProcessWindowStyle.Hidden;
startInfo.FileName = "adb";
startInfo.Arguments = command;

Process process = new Process();
process.StartInfo = startInfo;
process.Start();
```

In the above code, the `adb` program is executed in a hidden window using the `ProcessWindowStyle.Hidden` property. The ADB command is passed as an argument using the `Arguments` property.

Note: Make sure that the `adb` program is installed on your computer and the environment variable is set correctly.

To join multiple ADB commands in C#, you can use the `&&` operator to concatenate them. Here's an example code:

```
using System.Diagnostics;

// Specify the ADB commands to be sent
string command = "adb devices && adb shell am start -n com.example.app/.MainActivity";

// Execute the ADB commands
ProcessStartInfo startInfo = new ProcessStartInfo();
startInfo.WindowStyle = ProcessWindowStyle.Hidden;
startInfo.FileName = "cmd.exe";
startInfo.Arguments = "/C " + command;

Process process = new Process();
process.StartInfo = startInfo;
process.Start();
```

In the above code, the `&&` operator is used to join two ADB commands, `adb devices` and `adb shell am start -n com.example.app/.MainActivity`. We then concatenate the commands into a single string variable, `command`.

The `cmd.exe` program is executed to run the ADB commands, which are passed as arguments using the `/C` option. The `ProcessWindowStyle.Hidden` property hides the console window when executing the command.

Note: Make sure that you have installed ADB and added the path in the environment variable.

To achieve this, you'll need to set up a server-side system to facilitate communication between your C# Windows app and the Android app over the internet. One approach is to use a web server and API.

Here are the steps to create a C# Windows app and an Android app that communicate over the internet using a web server:

1. Create a server-side API:

You can use platforms like ASP.NET Core to create a web API hosted on a server. Follow this tutorial to create a simple web API: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/aspnet/core/tutorials/first-web-api.

2. Host the server-side API:

You can deploy your web API to a hosting provider like Azure, AWS, or any other provider that supports ASP.NET Core hosting. Here's the guide to deploy an ASP.NET Core web API to Azure: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/aspnet/core/tutorials/publish-to-azure-webapp-using-vs.

3. Modify the C# Windows app:

Update your C# Windows app to send an HTTP request (e.g., using HttpClient) with the dial code data to the API you created. Here's an example of sending an HTTP request with HttpClient: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/tutorials/console-webapiclient.

4. Create an Android app with Xamarin:

Follow the steps from my previous response to create a Xamarin.Android app.

5. Add internet permission to your Xamarin.Android app:

Open the AndroidManifest.xml file in your Xamarin.Android project and add the following line within the `<manifest>` element and outside the `<application>` element:

```xml
<uses-permission android:name="android.permission.INTERNET" />
```

6. Modify the Android app:

Update your Android app to listen for updates from the server-side API. You can periodically poll the server for new commands, or use WebSocket or SignalR for real-time communication. Here's a tutorial on real-time communication between a Xamarin.Android app and an ASP.NET Core server using SignalR: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/aspnet/core/tutorials/signalr.

7. Dial a code in the Android app:

When your Android app receives a code from the server, use the `TelephonyManager` or `ACTION_CALL` Intent (with `CALL_PHONE` permission) to dial the code. Note that calling a number programmatically requires the user's consent and appropriate permissions.

Sample code to dial a number:

