To open a URL and then run code on that URL using HTML and JS, you can use `window.open()` in JS to open the URL in a new window or tab, and then use `window.postMessage()` to communicate between the parent window and the child window.

Example:

HTML:

```
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
	<title>My Page</title>
	<script src="script.js"></script>
</head>
<body>
	<h1>Welcome to my page!</h1>
	<button onclick="openWindow()">Click me</button>
</body>
</html>
```

JS (script.js):

```
function openWindow() {
	// open new window with URL and name
	var newWindow = window.open("https://www.google.com/", "My Window");

	// wait for child window to load
	newWindow.onload = function() {
		// send message to child window
		newWindow.postMessage("Hello from parent window", "*");
	};

	// receive message from child window
	window.addEventListener("message", receiveMessage, false);

	function receiveMessage(event) {
		// check message origin and data
		if (event.origin !== "https://www.google.com" || event.data !== "Hello from child window") {
			return;
		}
		// code to be executed on child window with URL
		alert("Code executed on child window with URL");
	}
}
```

In this example, when the user clicks the button, the `openWindow` function is called, which opens a new window with the specified URL and name. When the child window loads, the function sends a message to the child window using `postMessage()`. The parent window also listens for messages from the child window using `addEventListener()`. When the child window sends a message back to the parent window, the `receiveMessage` function is called, which checks the message origin and data, and executes the desired code on the child window with the specified URL.

Note that this example assumes that the child window with the specified URL is hosted on the same domain and protocol as the parent window. If you want to communicate between windows hosted on different domains or protocols, you may need to set up CORS (Cross-Origin Resource Sharing) or use other techniques like JSONP.

To run JS code on a new URL using HTML and JS, you can use the `window.location.href` property to redirect the page to the desired URL, and then execute your JS code on that page.

Example:

HTML:

```
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
	<title>My Page</title>
	<script src="script.js"></script>
</head>
<body>
	<h1>Welcome to my page!</h1>
	<button onclick="redirectToNewUrl()">Click me</button>
</body>
</html>
```

JS (script.js):

```
function redirectToNewUrl() {
	// redirect to new URL
	window.location.href = "https://www.google.com";

	// wait for page to load using onload event
	window.onload = function() {
		// code to be executed on new URL
		alert("Code executed on new URL");
	};
}
```

In this example, when the user clicks the button, the `redirectToNewUrl` function is called, which redirects the page to the specified URL using the `window.location.href` property. When the new page has finished loading, the `window.onload` event is fired, and the function executes the desired code on the new page using `alert()`.

Note that when you redirect to a new page using `window.location.href`, the current page will be unloaded and replaced by the new page. This means that any JS code running on the current page will stop executing, and you will need to redefine your functions and variables on the new page if you want them to be available.

