Yes, that's correct! `$(document).ready()` is a jQuery function that waits for the document, i.e., the HTML page, to be fully loaded and ready before running the JavaScript code inside it. This ensures that all the elements on the page, including images, videos, and other media, have been loaded and can be manipulated by the code.

This function is commonly used to execute code that modifies the DOM or attaches event handlers to elements, more precisely, it ensures that the DOM is ready to be modified. Here's an example:

```
$(document).ready(function() {
   //code here will execute when the document is ready
});
``` 

Note that in modern jQuery versions, you can also use the shorthand for `$(document).ready(function(){})`, which is `$(function(){})`. They both achieve the same thing - waiting for the document to be ready before running the code inside the function.

To hide both the button and paragraph elements when the button is clicked, you can simply modify the jQuery code inside the `$(document).ready()` function as follows:

```
$(document).ready(function(){
  $("button").click(function(){
    // hide both button and p elements
    $("button, p").hide();
  });
});
```

In this case, `$("button, p")` selects both button and paragraph elements, and the `.hide()` method hides all the selected elements.

