Yes, that's correct! `this` refers to the particular element that triggered the event listener. In the example you posted earlier, `$(this).hide()` is called when the button is clicked, so `this` refers to the button element.

In the jQuery docs, `this` is often referred to as the "DOM element" that is being acted upon by the jQuery method. In other words, when you use `$(this)` in your code, you are creating a jQuery object around the specific element that was clicked or acted upon, so that you can then apply jQuery methods to that element.

For example, if you wanted to change the text of the clicked button to "Loading..." when it was clicked, you could do something like this:

```
$(document).ready(function(){
  $("button").click(function(){
    $(this).text("Loading...").attr("disabled", true);
  });
});
```

In this case, `$(this).text("Loading...")` changes the text of the button that was clicked to "Loading...", and `.attr("disabled", true)` disables the button by setting the `disabled` attribute to `true`.

